segments.text: You were talking about that being the only form of entertainment.
Can you think of any others that might have gone on that the boys did or the faculty amused themselves with?
Well, of course, the faculty played bridge, or whist at that time it was called, and had formal dances using the missile.
I mean, the... Shirley...
for the faculty.
The students were going to have a dance.
They used the mess hall.
Now, you were single for how long there?
Well, I was single all along then.
I came back here single after the war.
I didn't marry until 21.
Did the single faculty members ever date any of the girls in Bryan?
Or did they have time to get out?
Oh, my goodness.
Why, man?
Dear human.
Oh, well, I know that, but I was just wondering if that's where they went to brine.
Sure, well, there was a trotter line.
Were there lots of single girls in brine then?
Well, I would say there were plenty for the faculty.
Some of them married the faculty men, some of them married students.
Some of those girls in brine married students, and some did marry tall.
Well, I don't know.
None of this stuff I'm telling you is of any value.
You ask a question that they have dances.
Yes, the men, we'd have a dance at the Shirley, and we'd go down, get our dates and walk them down to the trolley line and rack them out on the trolley.
11.30, we'd take them back.
Then we'd walk home.
All the way from Bryan?
Sure.
It was about, what, six miles?
Five.
Five.
Take about?
About an hour and a half.
About an hour and a half.
Yeah.
But you know, all the ladies, after having a dance with the beautiful lady, you could walk ten miles.
So you all get back then?
1, 2 o'clock the next morning.
Oh, yes.
These dances were usually, what, on a Saturday night?
Oh, yes.
They'd be on a Saturday night.
I see.
Now, later on, we began to have dances in the gymnasium.
I don't know how much you got on Charlie Moran.
Very little.
Charlie Moran's one of the great men that's ever been to this institution.
What do you remember about him?
Everything good.
Everything good.
Could you tell us a little bit about it?
Well, I came here, and Charlie, his wife, and his son, Charles Jr., was living upstairs over the, over the Shirley.
And Charlie participated in our after supper boxing contest.
Oh now, you all boxed after supper?
Oh yes.
I see.
Where did you all box?
Where did this take place?
In the Shirley?
Oh no, no.
Outdoors or if it's in some of the rooms in the Shirley Annex.
I saw John Griswold, a professor of veterinary, no, animal husbandry,
hit Si Evans on the chin and dropped him behind the trunk, and we had to almost tear the building down to get Si out the back of the trunk.
Oh, my goodness.
How often did this take place?
Every evening?
It could be every evening.
There was no set.
There was just nothing set about it.
Did everybody participate?
Oh, no.
No, no.
There were a bunch of fellas that were...
more lace on their pants that wouldn't participate.
But Charlie would, and he'd get in there, and Charlie'd get mad, and that was fun, to haul up and suck him and make him mad.
But getting mad didn't last.
It was fun to wrap one around his ear,
You say that Coach Moran participated.
Was he a good boxer?
Fair.
None of them were going to challenge Ed Hamlin.
Neither or none of them would have challenged Ed Hamlin.
They didn't have, when I came here, football was played on the drill field.
It was.
And they passed the hat to get any funds that was, to get men.
Baseball was played on the drill field.
They passed the hat.
Now this is the drill field you're talking about, the one that's now in front of the MSC?
Yeah.
Okay.
Now, in the summer of 1911, a boy by the name of Kyle, who was on the board of directors, an uncle to E.J.
Kyle, arranged for a bit of land to be set aside
for the athletic department.
Up until that time, they had not had an athletic director.
Charlie was the first athletic director.
Now this Kyle you spoke of, do you remember his initials?
Dr. Allen Kyle.
I see.
And where was he?
He was Houston.
He was in Houston.
Do you remember anything else about him?
What he did for a living?
He was a doctor.
Oh, he was an M.D.
I see.
Okay, go ahead.
Well,
They have a football game, and it rained.
The drill field wasn't fit to drill on for quite a while.
So in the interim, until they got this field that Kyle had set out, they moved around the corner about where those tennis courts are,
If you know, as you go around the corner from MSC, heading down toward the...
There are a bunch of tennis courts over there.
It's behind.
It's back of Kyle Field.
No, it's this way.
Now, wait a minute.
I'll take it back.
They've got an athletic dormitory going in there now.
Okay, I know what you're talking about.
All right.
That used to be... You see...
I'm behind you.
I'm out of date.
But that was...
And they set that out to play football on.
I see.
And the fall of 1911, they played football there.
Charlie, by midnight requisitioning, begging, borrowing, stealing, and everything possible, got together enough stuff to enclose
This athletic field that was set out by members of the board of directors under the instance of Dr. Kyle.
Now, you're talking about not where the tennis courts are, but now we're talking about the new place.
I'm talking about Kyle Field.
That area right there.
We're inside of Kyle Field now.
Now, that was not originally college land?
Oh, yes.
It was old college land, but it was set aside.
it was part of the agronomy, a test lab.
He took it away from them and gave it to the athletic department.
I see.
Since he was on the board of directors, he could do this.
Oh yes, oh yes.
And don't get the idea that E.J.
Kyle had anything to do with this, although in 1925, after his uncle died, he went to the board of directors and asked the board of directors to
say that Kyle Field was named for him.
And they did.
And they did.
So it is named for him.
No.
In a way.
No.
Well, I understand the point, but yeah, I see what he did.
All right.
Now, Charlie called that area Kyle Field.
But, as I said,
by every way he could do it.
He didn't have any money.
Use of students for labor, faculty members for labor, all of it shelled out money.
I'd give him, of course, I'd give him something down to as much as 50 cents.
And he'd take up a collection of something.
He needed something, and the fellow...
He just passed the hat.
The hat, yeah.
And with his energy and hard work of his own, they built a gymnasium that had, believe it or not, hot and running water and a place to play basketball.
My goodness.
It's a good building.
It's well put together.
It's a double floor deal.
Mm-hmm.
And the faculty then moved their dancers from the Shirley down there.
We just had to walk another half mile, that's all.
It didn't make any difference in those days.
And the students still continue.
When they had Thanksgiving and Easter and the final,
or in the domes or in the missiles.
But Charlie, in the fall of 1912, now you're going to have to check these dates.
I'm not sure about this date.
I think in the fall of 1912, he brought Leo Betray in, who was an All-American football player from Chicago and All-American basketball, I think.
But at any rate, he was a basketball player.
He may not have been an All-American.

to help him as a coach they had no basketball team so ron hanson a student here had played basketball in houston and they tagged him for captain he had some experience and they organized a basketball team
But they had nobody to play until, oh, I reckon, I guess Bill was the first intercollegiate they played.
There again, you'd have to check the figures on it because.
But in order for the boys to have some practice, a bunch of the younger instructors would organize them a basketball team and played them.
I see.
And most of them, as I told, where are you from?
Corpus Christi.
Well, there was a Baptist preacher in Galveston that was one of the most famous Baptist preachers in Texas.
And I told Bailey Stone that when I came here, he tried to take my place off the Best Man Athletic Club's basketball team, but he couldn't.
He wasn't bloodthirsty enough.
Because you take a move there, you have a fellow playing basketball, and he's supposed to have some skin places.
coming off and a little blood flowing.
Well, this bunch of instructors had been taught, they had come up under that rough little way of playing.
Well, in 1920 they changed all that, and even today it's rough now.
But if you'd have left the rules like they were back there, there would have been mayhem on every game.
Basketball was a contact sport then?
Oh, yes.
You get the ball, I take it away from you.
I see.
There weren't any fouls then, huh?
Yes, there were fouls, but if you had that ball and I got my hand on it, you and I would have a wrestling match, and that was not a foul.
I see.
And?
And you played on this team for how long?
Well, this is just this year, that one year.
That one year.
Because of the fact that the students, after that, they had plenty of competition.
And they had plenty of substitutes and so on.
But the faculty helped make the basketball team in, I think it was 1912.
Remember anything else about Charlie Moran?
And Charlie, as I said, was a baseball coach.
And he did not attempt to coach baseball.
D. Tracher did that.
Charlie coached baseball, and he had a good baseball team.
So he had football and baseball.
Yeah.
And about 1913, I guess it was, maybe 14, I don't remember, A&M played the University of Texas two or three times,
the ground up with them.
And the University of Texas complained that Charlie Moran was coaching dirty football, and they wouldn't play A&M anymore until they got rid of Charlie Moran.
And A&M College got rid of one of the best coaches they ever had.
He was fired here?
Yeah, he was fired.
Do you know where he went?
College, and I never saw Charlie anymore until A&M Beach Center College in Christmas of 21-22 in Dallas.
And I just married.
I took my wife over to that dressing room, and she is very, very timid and sensitive, but I dragged her in that room to see Charlie, and these men had undershirts and so on, and
She'd be blushed all over, but she met Charlie Moran.
It was the only time she ever met him.
I saw Charlie a couple more times after that.
Charlie got up off the bed and quit cussing and walked over and put his arm around her and kissed her.
That scared her.
Well, he was, but he made the athletic department.
Sounds like he built it almost single-handedly.
He did, he did.
You can't say anything against Charlie for me.
That dirty playing that the university hollered was a case of pot calling the kettle black.
And where the dirty playing has been, the university has done more than they shall.
And if A&M violates the rules of today, the interscholastic rules, collegiate rules today, the least bit, we get censured.
The University of Texas busts them a little wide open, come in and go in, and nobody says anything.
Am I prejudiced?
Yes, I'm prejudiced.
That's not what you mean.
All right, now I don't see where they are at either.
Coming back here, Perea,
It was just at the interim, and Grisel came in.
Grisel had a doctor's degree in education, and he came here.
He was teaching in Navasota as superintendent of the schools.
They brought him here, and he came in with a lot of friction from top to bottom.
with not so much from the students as from the faculty.
And he gave here and didn't give there, and he finally worked that out until things were very, worked out very nicely.
And he begun to build the institution as an educational institution.
And he left here in 26, 25,
to go to Oklahoma, and taking his place was Walton.
Walton was another great man.
I had a man tell me when I was in Amarillo, we're going to have to get rid of Walton.
I said, what's the matter?
We want so-and-so to be, him to hire so-and-so, and he won't do it.
I turned to this man and I said, you want to congratulate the state of Texas on having a man as president of this institution that puts principle above politics?
The fellow looked at me and he said, I guess you're right.
But he didn't quit.
They kept nibbling at him because he would not.
Hire certain individuals.
Apologies.
And he was one of the strong men.
A lot of folks didn't like him.
You go down there and go in his office, and he might run you out and just climb all over you.
I never had Gibb do that to me.
The reason is, if I went in to ask Gibb for a favor, I had a whole lot more bricks in my pocket than he had in his.
I knew what I wanted, why I wanted, what it was going to cost, and everything about it.
Most of these folks that went in and asked for appropriations from him really hadn't done their midnight oil work.
And he would know more about what they wanted than they did, and he'd come and run them out and tell them not to come back until they knew what they wanted.
And I found a gib by Jimenez.
If he said yes, he meant yes.
And that's something that in places of that type is rather unusual.
You thought then that he was very fair and honest?

very have you gotten any different ideas no no i think there's some people i've run into people who didn't like him but purely on personality not on anything that is it he he'd run him out of his office i mean run him out
Get out.
Get out.
Get out.
I did have one comment that Gibb really created the Department of Chemical Engineering.
Who did?
Gibb Gilchrist.
He did more to start it.
No.
No?
No.
Gibb Gilchrist did what had been promised.
By who?
Bazell.
Bazell?
And that is to separate the Department of Chemical Engineering from the Department of Chemistry.
And when I went into the Extension Service, that's the first thing that was done.
And the fellow that they brought in here was a fellow by the name of Ruth.
It was not a clean-cut schism.
They quit calling it the Department of Chemistry and Chemical Engineering and were calling it the Department of Chemistry and the Department of Chemical Engineering, but it was still under Hedges.
And Ruth got the notion that he was the last word in the operation of the Department of Chemical Engineering.
And Hedges didn't have that idea.
real quick.
And they brought John Lindsey in.
If you've talked to John Lindsey, who was head of the Department of Chemical Engineering, he came here, I would say, in 37.
Could you tell us a little bit about C.C.
Hedges?
Who?
C.C.
Hedges.
Could you tell us a little bit about him?
He has kind of an interesting reputation.
There again, you're talking to a fellow that thinks Hedges is handed down from heaven.
Do you think he was a good administrator there?
Yes, he was, but he was not amenable to, you might say, give and take.
Hedges came here in the fall
1912, I guess.
No.
Could have been.
Yeah.
As professor of agricultural chemistry and organic.
And they fired G.S.
Fraps at that time out of the department, put him back on an experiment station to stay.
And what are you grinning about?
Fraps is one of my favorites.
Go ahead.
I've been reading about him.
I never met the man, don't know him.
He was long gone by the time I ever arrived, but I read a lot of his stuff, and he's kind of an interesting person.
Do you know anybody that liked him?
I haven't met anybody that liked him, but he wrote prolifically.
And 50% of them should have stayed in the...
typewriter.
It may well be.
I'm not a chemist, but I've been going through a lot of stuff and just wrote and wrote and wrote forever and I was just wondering what kind of a man he was.
A self-made son of a bitch.
Take that off of this.
It's kind of like the old story that some of us are born bastards and some of us make it meritorious.
You take that off of this.
Okay, I will.
But
Hedges, I told you that Blake gave me a bunch of bologna, why I should stay.
Well, he gave Hedges the same stuff.
Hedges told me, I said, well, I went through that, too.
But he was made head of the department, and Blake left the following year, in 13.
Hedges was made head of the department.
He was a perfectionist, I guess I would like to use that word, perfectionist, and couldn't tolerate sloppy work.
And as a result, there were a lot of fellows that didn't like Hedges.
I came back in 1919 as head of the department of chemical engineering, the division of chemical engineering.
He gave me almost as near as he ever gave anybody free hand to do as I pleased.
And he had a stiff leg.
I could have killed him for that.
He fell on the stairway and sprained his knee.
I helped pick him up, put him in a car, and told him to take him to the hotel.
You know what that sucker did?
The fellow started off and he said, stop.
He got out of the car and came on back with that knee.
in the shape it was, in a horrible shape.
That night, I put a towel, it's not a hot towel, I just took a wet towel, warm, put it around his leg, and I said, you leave it there until morning.
I said, I'm going to sweat that knee down.
I said, that rag is not hot.
It'll get warm from the fever in your knee.
Next morning, that rag was on the floor.
Said it got too hot.
He came back here and went to a doctor, and the doctor drew the water off of the knee, and that was it.
So he had a stiff knee.
But, and he was a firecracker.
In a way, he'd fly off the handle real quick.
But Harold Brayton and I didn't pay any attention to it.
Just let him blow.
Other people couldn't tolerate that.
So I imagine you have a lot of people that didn't care much for Hedges.
That's interesting to get both sides' personality, though.
I thought well and all of him.
And, well, personal things come in there, lots of them.
By the way, Bolton taught me physics in Mississippi A&M.
Surprising how many people from Mississippi A&M showed up here.
Well, you take, Cornell was from Mississippi.
He was from Starkville.
Harrington was from Starkville.
Cornell went from here to Oklahoma.
During that period,
I would say at one time we had 20% of the younger staff of the Mississippi A&M.
I wonder why.
Well, there was Bolton and Harrington.
They knew the men.
They didn't know the others.
And Mississippi, at that time, Mississippi A&M,
was one of the leading Southern colleges.
They faded.
I thought of picking it up again.
They've become what now, Mississippi State?
Yeah, it's Mississippi State.
But as I said, Bolton, you'd probably get a better, as good a picture from others as you will from me, and we was taking time then.
Tom Harrington graduated from engineering in 1923.
And we got him a job in Texas Company.
In 24, I believe it was, he showed up here.
He had quit, and he wanted to teach.
That's what he wanted to do, he wanted to teach.
So we put him on.
and he finally wound up, as you see here, president of the institution.
And Tom did a good work.
Tom was not, was there in the beginning of the explosion and was not fully
Didn't fully use it, but Earl Rudder took full use of the explosion.
That's financial.
You take, Earl Rudder got a hundred million dollars.
Well, you take a hundred million dollars and drop it on the campus at A&M College and something's going to yield.
And since that time, I imagine that the university, the university has gotten a neighborhood of 200, get us a thousand, I mean a million.
right in the neighborhood of 200 million dollars from the government.
And that, in all, in all payments.
There may be more.
But you take that amount of money and put it in a little community like this, something's going to give.
And you've got these high-rise buildings there that originally didn't have money enough to make a low-rise building there.
You see?
It's really grown to the extent that at one time, about a year and a half ago, we had more buildings, we had more money in buildings under construction than the campus was worth in 1950.
Oh, yes.
Oh, my Lord, yes.
In 1914, they were figuring on giving it away and moving the college up between Dallas and Fort Worth.
I didn't know that.
Who was the instigator of this?
I don't remember.
Do you remember the Old Main fire?
Do you remember the Old Main fire?
Oh, yes.
When it burned down.
Do you know anything about the story of that fire?
Do you have any idea why it burned or maybe who burned it if it wasn't intentional?
Well, anything that I would say other than what you know would be just supposition because I don't know.
I don't think anybody does.
It's...
It's a mean thing, but as I said, I wouldn't want to even speculate at all, because I will say this.
In fact, in the early days, there were no women working on the campus.
To put stenographers on the campus would put temptation in the minds of the students, and that couldn't be done.
In 19, oh, I guess 1912, the Experiment Station wanted a, the college library had a woman assistant librarian, who later became Mrs. W.H.
Thomas.
a the uh experiment station had a woman librarian who also did a little writing for harrington and younger but officially the wall stenographers were men well the name of uh spence nagle had a
stenographer, a man, that lived upstairs, anti-Godlin down the hall from me.
One night, door opened, he came there and he said, I said, what are you doing in here, Jeffrey?
He says, I think there's a fire somewhere.
I threw, hit the floor running.
I said, where?
again.
Follow me, guy, follow me."
Well, then his bed was blazing.
I picked it up and threw it out the window and gave him a boot.
I said, next time you stay sober.
But that wasn't, at that time Jeffrey didn't do that.
And they started to investigate.
Now this can't be documented because it's just simply, it's not hearsay and yet it's
Well, go ahead.
It actually occurred when the board of directors were very unhappy.
They hadn't been able to get a stenographer to take the testimony.
And Spence said, well, I've got a stenographer to take the testimony.
He sent for Jeffrey.
Jeffrey came in and was sort of like this, and what you want
the Board of Directors chairman, I can't think of his name, said, can you take dictation of this testimony?
He said, let her roll, guy, let her roll.
And that is when they got the testimony they got with Jeffrey Ticket.
Now, he lasted here a couple of years.
Oh, about a year.
I named him off, and last time he was president of the bank.
He's done very well.
He quit drinking, and he's done very well.
Well, let's say I got your career up to 1935, and you went into the extension service.
Could you tell us about that if you've got time to?
You know, that's now, we're getting over into Baron Moonshousen's work.
Who's that?
The world's greatest fibber.
Oh, okay.
As I said, I was very unhappy.
I couldn't get students jobs after four years.
And Director Martin of the Extension Service conceived the idea
that if they would build community centers out in the country from town that were self-supporting, that it would help the agriculture of the state.
And, oh, just as a hobby,
I'd been tanning lots of leather.
And he came in and asked me if I could teach farmers to tan leather.
I said, sure, if they'll do it.
I said, a lot of work to it.
He said, folks, we're not worrying about work now.
They want to submit to goods.
Well, I don't know whether I did right or wrong.
My wife never did like it, but she tolerated it.
I went over to the extension service, had a pretty nice raise in pay, and started off as a leather specialist, teaching writing and teaching farmers to turn leather.
Tau hide sold for 25 cents, opossum skin for 35.
And I've got some leather out there in the garage now that was built, that I was made in 1936.
That leather is as good as any leather you ever saw.
And we made, I helped tan and directed the tanning of over 200,000 hides.
And these are car hides, not skins.
We don't count skins.
I think some of the romantic
phase is in the skins.
Women buy those tan skins and made themselves with fur coats.
Yeah, lots of them made.
I used to have to, they'd bring them to me, and they just didn't wear but a sack.
And I'd haul up and gather them and show them how to gather them.
And they'd wind up with a coat that would fit just like his, just about as good as the one he'd buy.
But Martin, and in addition to that, he started in, not only that, he directed me to see what I could do about making, improving quality of syrup.
And I'll guarantee you that I can take sorghum syrup and make you think it's ribbon cane.
And it's easily done.
Lord knows how much syrup I have made and directed.
And I'm still getting letters from folks wanting to know how to make syrup.
Did you ever do any work for the corn products company in there?
No.
I don't know.
O.B.
died about 36 or 37, and H.H.
Williamson went into the job.
Bill didn't see any, oh by the way, these, we made the community centers where the farmers would themselves do all the work and yet then get the benefit from it.
There's one of those over here in Houston County.
There were two or three of those around.
And they functioned in the way that they were supposed to.
Farmers by Jimenez would turn the leather there and wind up with hides and leather goods that they could never have bought.
Make them themselves.
Down here is a human interest story.
Okay.
